<li id="cite_note-71"><span class="mw-cite-backlink"><b><a href="#cite_ref-71">^</a></b></span> <span class="reference-text"><cite class="citation web cs1"><a rel="nofollow" class="external text" href="https://www.imf.org/en/Topics/climate-change/energy-subsidies">"Fossil Fuel Subsidies"</a>. <i>IMF</i><span class="reference-accessdate">. Retrieved <span class="nowrap">2 January</span> 2024</span>. <q>Raising fuel prices to their fully efficient levels reduces projected global fossil fuel CO2 emissions 43 percent below baseline levels in 2030—or 34 percent below 2019 emissions. This reduction is in line with the 25-50 percent reduction in global GHGs below 2019 levels needed by 2030 to be on track with containing global warming to the Paris goal of 1.5-2C.</q></cite><span title="ctx_ver=Z39.88-2004&amp;rft_val_fmt=info%3Aofi%2Ffmt%3Akev%3Amtx%3Ajournal&amp;rft.genre=unknown&amp;rft.jtitle=IMF&amp;rft.atitle=Fossil+Fuel+Subsidies&amp;rft_id=https%3A%2F%2Fwww.imf.org%2Fen%2FTopics%2Fclimate-change%2Fenergy-subsidies&amp;rfr_id=info%3Asid%2Fen.wikipedia.org%3AFossil+fuel+phase-out" class="Z3988"></span></span>
